ssword" class=3D"prismic-a break-words underline hover:text-han-purple">the=
 definition is typically hiding in plain sight</a>, and don=E2=80=99t lose =
heart!</p><p role=3D"paragraph" class=3D"prismic-p text-base mt-3 lg:text-l=
g lg:mt-6">Depending on the difficulty and&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.nyti=
mes.com/2017/10/07/crosswords/variety-cryptic-crossword.html" class=3D"pris=
mic-a break-words underline hover:text-han-purple">the specific newspaper e=
ditor</a>, you might find cryptic crossword clues with weird traits like th=
ese:</p><ul class=3D"prismic-list list-cws-disc"><li>Look for&nbsp;<strong =
class=3D"prismic-strong">anagrams</strong>, where you simply need to rearra=
nge letters to find the answer. For instance, =E2=80=9Ccash trims=E2=80=9D =
would be =E2=80=9CChristmas.=E2=80=9D</li><li>Many editors like&nbsp;<stron=
g class=3D"prismic-strong">homophones</strong>, which are words that sound =
like other words but are spelled differently. =E2=80=9CTheir,=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9Cthey=E2=80=99re,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=9D are homophones.=
</li><li><strong class=3D"prismic-strong">Reversals&nbsp;</strong>involve r=
eversing the letters of the clue to get the answer. The reverse of =E2=80=
=9Cera=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=9Care,=E2=80=9D for example.</li><li><strong clas=
s=3D"prismic-strong">Deletions</strong>&nbsp;involve deleting one or two le=
tters to get a different answer. For instance, =E2=80=9Cmend=E2=80=9D minus=
 a letter could be =E2=80=9Cend=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cmen.=E2=80=9D</li><li>=
<strong class=3D"prismic-strong">Containers</strong>&nbsp;imply that you=E2=
=80=99ll need to insert a word inside of another word, usually indicated in=
 the clue by words like =E2=80=9Cwithin=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Csurrounding.=
=E2=80=9D</li></ul><p role=3D"paragraph" class=3D"prismic-p text-base mt-3 =
